 We do this by choosing a bandwidth h and then, using a grid search, finding
 the TC such that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TC_{t+h/2}=min_{TC}\sum_{t=t}^{t+h}\left(\left\Vert P_{t}^{A}-P_{t}^{B}\right\Vert -\hat{\rho}\left\Vert P_{t-1}^{A}-P_{t-1}^{B}\right\Vert I_{\left\Vert P_{t-1}^{A}-P_{t-1}^{B}\right\Vert >TC}+\left\Vert P_{t}^{A}-P_{t}^{B}\right\Vert I_{\left\Vert P_{t-1}^{A}-P_{t-1}^{B}\right\Vert >TC}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After this, the estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $TC{}_{t}$
\end_inset

 are smoothed using a standard local polynomial regression.
 This leads to a new series of transaction costs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{TC_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 This time variant transaction cost, together with the initial speed of
 adjustment could be seen as a first characterization of the degree of market
 integration.
 However, now that we have a more flexible estimate of the transaction cost,
 we can use this estimate the update our estimate of the adjustment speed.
 In particular: 
\end_layout

